<h1 style="text-align:center">Installing the <strong><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></span><span style="color:#000099"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></span><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></span><span style="color:#000099"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></span></strong> Codex</h1><p>The <span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span> Codex is a complete integrated development system for coding websites. It can be run locally in your own computer or installed on your server; the only prerequisite is a recent copy of PHP.</p><h2>Installation on a regular PC</h2><p>First download the <a href="http://codex.easycoder.software/codex.zip">Codex</a> archive into an empty folder.</p><p>Unzip the archive.</p><p>Open a command line shell and navigate to the folder where you unzipped the archive. Then type</p><p><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">php -S localhost:8000</span></p><p>You should get confirmation that the PHP server started.</p><p>Now go to your browser and type <span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">localhost:8000</span> into the address bar. Hit Enter. The Codex should start up.</p><h2>Installation on a server</h2><p>Download the <a href="http://codex.easycoder.software/codex.zip">Codex</a> archive into the root of your website.</p><p>Unzip the archive.</p><p>Type the URL of your server into your browser address bar and hit Enter. The Codex should start up.</p><p>If you need help, join our Slack channel by clicking <a href="https://join.slack.com/t/easycoder-software/shared_invite/enQtNTU5ODEwOTQ5NTU0LWQ1NWVkOTUxOGQ3NzJmNDI1ZGRlOTdmMjc1NDAxMGIwMTFjODg1ZDJhODEzMzUzODc2MDNlZWU4NmYyZWRlOWI">here</a>.</p><hr /><h1 style="text-align:center">Script strategies</h1><p>There are two main strategies for using EasyCoder scripts, as follows:</p><h2>Script in BODY</h2><p>The simplest approach is to embed your script in the body of the page. The basic outline is</p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;head&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;meta name=&quot;viewport&quot; content=&quot;width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;My scripted web page&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;script type=&#39;text/javascript&#39; src=&#39;/easycoder/easycoder.js&#39;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/head&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;body&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;pre id=&quot;easycoder-script&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:80px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">alert `Hello, world!` </span></span>&lt;----- This is the EasyCoder script</p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/pre&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/body&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/html&gt;</span></span></p><p>A variant of this is where you add a script to a page that already contains HTML. The script will be added in its own preformatted block on the page. The location of the script in the page is not significant; it can be at the top, in the middle or at the bottom.</p><p>The main thing to note is that instead of the script creating DOM elements as in the Codex tutorials, these elements will in many cases already exist. So instead of using <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">create</span></span> you will use <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">attach</span></span>, giving the id of the element you want to attach to:</p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">create Button in Container</span></span></p><p>becomes</p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">attach Button to `ec-button`</span></span></p><p>The most common use of this strategy is probably where an existing page is being retrofitted with <span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span> script.</p><h2>Script from REST</h2><p>This second strategy is more powerful and carries many benefits. Here the script is not embedded in the page at all. Instead, all that is present is a &#39;boot loader&#39; that requests the script from the server using the <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">rest</span></span> command.</p><p>Here&#39;s what the simplest form of this page looks like:</p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;head&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;meta name=&quot;viewport&quot; content=&quot;width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;My scripted web page&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;script type=&#39;text/javascript&#39; src=&#39;/easycoder/easycoder.js&#39;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/head&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;body&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;pre id=&quot;easycoder-script&quot;&gt;</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:80px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">variable Script<br />rest get Script from `/resources/scripts/myscript`<br />run Script<br />stop</span></span></p><p style="margin-left:40px"><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/pre&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/body&gt;</span></span></p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">&lt;/html&gt;</span></span></p><p>Here the script (filename: <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">myscript</span></span>) is located in the <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">{site root}/resources/scripts</span></span> directory. When you write scripts in Codex, this is where they will be saved, allowing you to directly maintain your site code from any computer (including a smartphone).</p><p>If you can deal with the CORS issues you can use a complete URL to retrieve your script from a remote site, using the REST server (a PHP file) supplied with <span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">E</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">asy</span></strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">C</span></strong></span><span style="color:#000099"><strong><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">oder</span></strong></span>. The command looks like this:</p><p><span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">rest get Script from `_load/https:~~mysite.com~myscripts~home`</span></span></p><p>All forward slashes (/) except the one after <span style="color:#660000"><span style="font-family:Courier New,Courier,monospace">_load</span></span> must be replaced by tilde characters (~) as shown here.</p>